http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: Nebraska K-12 Fine Arts Standards: Theatre

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Fine Arts Standards, adopted on March 4, 2014.
Students will develop knowledge and skills applying the creative and collaborative process within theatre by crafting, performing, and responding to expressions of the human experience.
Create
Students will dramatize ideas and events through structured improvisation.
Identify an environment or event using body movement and sound (e.g., playground, grocery store, classroom).
Listen to a story and identify the problem.
Create, in a group, a tableau of a scene after hearing a fairytale.
Engage in creative play, using a given theme, to tell a story (e.g. sharing, safety, friendship).
Engage in creative play, using props, to tell a story.
Explore character through body movement (e.g., enact occupations, fairy tale characters).
Students will dramatize ideas and events with a beginning, middle, and end.
Create, in a group, an environment or event using body movement and sound (e.g., a forest, a baseball game) while working in a group.
Using dialogue and movement, retell a story with a clear beginning, middle, and end (e.g., nursery rhymes, fairy tales). Work in small groups.
Create three tableaus illustrating the beginning, middle, and end of a story and then connect them. Work in small groups.
Identify themes within theatrical works.
Write a short script incorporating narration and dialogue.
Show a character using body movement (e.g., age, personality, family role, occupation).
Students will dramatize ideas and events incorporating "the givens" (who, what, when, where, why).
Use readily available props to create "the where" of a story (e.g., table, chairs, silverware indicate a restaurant).

Plan and record, in small groups, an improvisation based on "the givens" of a scene (e.g., tell or present a story using a setting, characters and a series of events incorporating introduction, climax, resolution).
Develop a linear plot structure that introduces and resolves a conflict.
Create theatrical works to illustrate a theme within theatrical works.
Write a dialogue with two to four characters.
Use movement in conjunction with extraneous sounds and short phrases to demonstrate two distinct characters (e.g., movements/sounds of a soldier as compared to movements/sounds of a mother).
Students will dramatize ideas and events using linear and non-linear plot structures.
Design, develop, and use an environment with available materials appropriate to a scripted or improvised performance (e.g., plan and create a bus stop or a store front).
Create a storyboard of an event using non-linear plot structure.
Develop and refine, through improvisation, a short scene using linear plot structure.
Analyze themes within theatrical works and their social relevance to audiences (e.g., McCarthyism in Arthur Miller's The Crucible).

Adapt a section or scene for performance from a novel or short story using dialogue and/or narration (e.g., trial scene from To Kill A Mockingbird, "The Interview" from The Scarlet Letter, Speak, "The Lottery").

Plan and rehearse an invented, historical or fictional character using posture, movement, facial expression, gestures, vocal choice, costume, make-up, hair, props, and space (e.g., living history monologue, Miracle Worker, Of Mice and Men, Pony Boy from The Outsiders)
Perform
Students will explore ideas and events through creative play.
Demonstrate expressive speech/vocal variety by sharing a personal experience.
Follow instructor's oral instructions (e.g., speak clearly, stay focused on scene).
Using classroom furniture and materials arrange a setting for a story as a group.
Identify how a character conveyed his/her feelings and emotions.
Students will perform ideas and events with a beginning, middle, and end.
Demonstrate expressive reading using vocal variety (glossary) (e.g., read short passage aloud).
Demonstrate characters (glossary) through movement (e.g., enact different ages, cartoon characters).
Create characters, individually, appropriate to a specific location a location.
Present a short script with narration and dialogue (e.g. readers' theatre).
Respectfully receive polite feedback from instructor and peers.
Design and craft a scenic element for an informal presentation (e.g., risers, prop, set piece, backdrop).
Identify one's own vocal and physical choices in expressing an emotion or idea (e.g., show a sound and movement that express sadness, happiness, anger).
Students will dramatize ideas and events incorporating "the givens" (who, what, when, where, why).
Establish character (glossary) and emotion through the use of rate, articulation, enunciation, projection, inflection, and movement.
Establish character and emotion through the use of facial expression, gesture, posture, and body movement (e.g., pantomime, emoting)
Rehearse and portray, in small groups, characters within a defined "where."
Deliver a scripted monologue to a focal point.
Modify performance based on teacher/director and peer response.
Design and craft a performance space including set and audience arrangement (e.g., use classroom furniture to create a courtroom in a proscenium, thrust, or arena).
Examine one's own effectiveness in a production/scene (e.g., keep a journal of acting choices, reflect on video of own performance).
Students will perform ideas and events through movement, speech, and staging for an intended audience.
Communicate character through the use of rate, articulation, enunciation, projection, inflection, blocking in a monologue or scene.

Communicate character, relationship, and objective through the use of blocking and facial expression (e.g., duet scene from Romeo & Juliet, Mama and Walter from Raisin in the Sun, Joe Mondragon and Sheriff from The Milagro Beanfield War).
Rehearse, refine, and perform a scripted play incorporating a designed environment and audience arrangement.
Polish and perform a monologue (glossary) based on the character developed in previous strand ("create character" FA 12.5.1.f).
Expand and develop character based on teacher/director comments.
Design and craft a performance space making effective use of available light, sound, and color.
Evaluate one's own effectiveness in a production/scene (e.g., taking director feedback and modifying performance).

Demonstrate understanding/respect for accepted procedures regarding responsible use/care of theatrical equipment/material (e.g., show awareness of fire codes regarding lights, curtains, paint storage, seating, scene shops; knowledge of rigging standards, safety regulations for use of power tools and other equipment).
Respond
Students will demonstrate understanding of audience/performance relationship.
Demonstrate active listening and theatre etiquette during a presentation (e.g., eagerness, interest, appropriate response [i.e., applause, laughter, quiet]).
Recall aspects of a performance.
Distinguish between a character and a performer.
Distinguish between fantasy and reality.
Share reactions to a moment or scene in a performance (e.g., verbal or reenactment).
Students will demonstrate effective audience/performance relationship.
Demonstrate respect for self and others (etiquette) in dramatic activities.
Discuss how the audience was impacted by the conflict and characters.
Recognize character traits and actor choices (e.g., how the character shows age, occupation, temperament).
Recognize theatrical works as either dramatic or comedic genres.
Articulate an emotional response to a component of a theatrical production (e.g., character, prop, costumes, song).
Students will analyze audience/performance relationship.
Construct, share, and use audience code of conduct including appropriate audience behavior and respect for physical space.
Identify, analyze, and discuss the impact of the stage space, casting, and technical elements.
Compare the effectiveness of a single actor's performance (i.e., physical/ vocal choices) as a variety of characters (e.g., Will Smith).
Classify theatrical works as dramatic, comedic, or musical theatre genres.
Discuss the impact on the audience of "willing suspension of disbelief" in a performance.
Students will analyze and evaluate audience/performance relationship.
Evaluate how audience conduct affects a theatrical performance.
Analyze and critique in part, or in its entirety, a live performance or recording of a live performance.
Evaluate how choices of the actor(s) impact audience understanding of a performance (e.g., Hamlet (Mel Gibson, Kenneth Branagh), multiple versions of Romeo & Juliet).
Differentiate among theatrical works as dramatic, comedic, musical theatre, or tragic genres.
Justify a personal reaction to a performance or recording of a live performance.
Connect
Students will recognize connections between theatre and society.
Describes how a performance or story represents the culture of its time. (e.g., cultural folktales).
Distinguish between real life vs. animation (e.g., Milan vs. live performance of The Lion King).
Watch a performance or cartoon and describe personal likes and dislikes.
Recognize at least two jobs in the performing arts.
Recognize authorship.
Students will identify connections between theatre and society.
Identify the cultural heritage of a particular work in theatre.
Recognize how performances reflect everyday circumstances (e.g., historical events, natural disasters, family relationships).
Watch a performance or film and explain personal likes and dislikes.
Identify how performance reflects culture and history (e.g., The Nutcracker, Peter and the Wolf).
Identify careers in the performing arts.
Understand the concept of intellectual property.
Students will analyze connections between theatre and society.
Understand the historical relevance of various theatrical forms (e.g., Greek and Roman theatre, Medieval, Renaissance).
Compare and contrast scripted and unscripted performances (e.g., situation comedy vs. reality shows).
Dramatize a traditional ritual (e.g., funeral from Our Town, wedding from Fiddler on the Roof, fire scene from Lord of the Flies).
Analyze how performance reflects culture and history (e.g., Oliver, The Color Purple).
Investigate responsibilities for specific careers in performing arts.
Demonstrate an understanding of the rights and responsibilities surrounding intellectual property (e.g., citing sources, paying royalties, receiving permission).
Students will analyze and evaluate connections between theatre and society.

Analyze the cultural and historical significance of theatrical forms as they have evolved over time, including contemporary theatre and pop culture (e.g., Romeo and Juliet influenced West Side Story).

Explain the differences between historical event and dramatization of the event (e.g., The Diary of Anne Frank vs. the play The Diary of Anne Frank, Salem Witch Trial records vs. The Crucible, letters of Abigail and John Adams vs. the musical 1776).
Examine the convergence of themes, ethics, aesthetics, and traditions in a theatrical work.
Analyze and evaluate cultural impact of theatre on society (e.g., A Raisin in the Sun, West Side Story).
Connect and draw conclusions about how various jobs in theatre contribute to the whole theatrical experience.

Respect intellectual property rights and identify entities vital to creation of, and advocacy for, theatre (e.g., respecting author intent, crediting authors, royalties, publishing companies, community theatres).
